class Solution {
public:
    string minimizeStringValue(string s) {
        vector<int> count(26, 0);
        string result;
        for (char c : s) {
            if (c == '?') {
                int minCost = INT_MAX;
                int minIndex = -1;
                for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
                    if (count[i] < minCost) {
                        minCost = count[i];
                        minIndex = i;
                    }
                }
                result += 'a' + minIndex;
                count[minIndex]++;
            } else {
                result += c;
                count[c - 'a']++;
            }
        }
        return result;
    }
};
```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: The solution iterates through the string once, maintaining a count of each character. When encountering a '?', it finds the character with the lowest count and assigns it to minimize the cost. This greedy approach ensures the lexicographically smallest string is produced when multiple options exist.

